# Baseline Agent Practices

**Precedence**: If the project has `CONTRIBUTING.md`, `AGENTS.md`, or equivalent, follow that first. These are universal defaults.

## Orientation Before Coding

1. Run `git remote -v` to classify repo topology:
   - **Upstream clone** (origin push = `UPSTREAM_DO_NOT_PUSH`): push to `fork` remote
   - **Own fork / personal**: push to `origin` normally
2. Scan for guidance (stop at first match per category):
   - AI rules: `AGENTS.md`, `CLAUDE.md`, `.agents/`, `.cursorrules`
   - Contribution: `.github/CONTRIBUTING.md`, `CONTRIBUTING.md`
   - PR template: `.github/PULL_REQUEST_TEMPLATE.md`
3. Discover build/test/lint commands (`package.json`, `Makefile`, `Cargo.toml`, etc.)
4. Run existing checks before making changes. Verify the build passes.

## Fail-Fast Policy

**No silent fallbacks for systems we control.** Fail immediately on errors.

```text
ERROR: [Component] [Operation] failed
CAUSE: [Root cause or violated invariant]
CONTEXT: File: [path:line], Variable: [name=value], State: [state]
REQUIRED ACTION: [What to fix]
DIAGNOSTIC: [Info or command]
```

Strict modes: `set -euo pipefail` (Bash), strict `tsconfig.json`. Never `|| true` or `except: pass`.

**External dependencies only**: Silent fallback acceptable for network/API calls — but MUST log a loud `WARNING` first.

```bash
# ✅ External fallback with warning
if ! fetch_external; then
    echo "WARNING: External unreachable — using fallback
CAUSE: Timeout / REQUIRED ACTION: Check network." >&2
    use_local_fallback
fi
```

```bash
# ❌ Silent internal fallback — forbidden
[ -f "$CONFIG" ] && source "$CONFIG" || source "/default/config"

# ✅ Loud internal failure
[ -f "$CONFIG" ] || { echo "ERROR: Config missing\nREQUIRED ACTION: Create $CONFIG" >&2; exit 1; }
source "$CONFIG"
```

## Warnings as Errors

Treat warnings as build-failing errors. Never suppress without user approval.

| ❌ Do NOT | ✅ Do Instead |
|---|---|
| `#[allow(unused)]` | Fix or stub + `TODO` |
| `@ts-ignore` | `@ts-expect-error` with detailed comment |
| `# type: ignore` | `mypy --warn-error` in CI |

Approved suppressions require a dated `TODO`:
```rust
// User approved (2026-03-14): Deferred per #42.
// TODO(2026-04-14): Remove once feature lands.
#[allow(dead_code)]
pub fn stub() {}
```

## Tech Debt Tracking

| Marker | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `TODO:` | Future work |
| `FIXME:` | Known bugs |
| `NOTE:` | Non-obvious context |
| `HACK:` | Temporary workarounds |

**ISO Date Required** for `HACK`, `FIXME`, and `TODO` on temporary/disabled features:
```
// HACK(2026-03-14): Workaround for upstream bug #1234
// TODO(2026-03-14): Re-enable caching after migration
```

**30-Day Rule**: When you encounter a dated marker older than 30 days, tell the user: how old it is, what it says, recommend reinvestigating.

## Git Safety

**Hard rules:**
- **NEVER commit on `main`/`master`** — always work on a named branch
- **NEVER force-push** unless explicitly asked
- Run `git branch --show-current` before any commit; if on default, branch first

**Branch naming:**

| Purpose | Pattern |
|---|---|
| Feature PR | `trahloc/feat/<name>` |
| Fix PR | `trahloc/fix/<name>` |
| Local throwaway | `local/<name>` |

**Commits**: Conventional Commits (`feat:`, `fix:`, `chore:`). Explain *why*.

**PR workflow:**
```bash
git fetch origin && git checkout -b trahloc/feat/<name> origin/main
# work, commit
git fetch origin && git rebase origin/main
git push fork trahloc/feat/<name> -u   # upstream clone
git push origin trahloc/feat/<name> -u # fork/personal
```

**Upstream clone setup:**
```bash
git config --local remote.origin.pushurl UPSTREAM_DO_NOT_PUSH
git remote add fork git@github.com:trahloc/<repo>.git
git checkout -b local/run origin/main
```

## Local File Management

Local configs belong in `.git/info/exclude` (not `.gitignore`) so they don't pollute upstream. Some repos commit these intentionally — check before excluding.

## Filesystem Operations

**Directory moves — rename, don't scatter.**
When moving an entire directory, rename it atomically. Never use glob patterns (`mv dir/* dst/`) — they silently skip dotfiles (`.git`, `.gitignore`, etc.) and destroy git history.

```bash
# ✅ Rename whole directory — preserves all dotfiles including .git
mv old_name/ new_location/old_name

# ❌ Glob scatter — silently drops .git and other dotfiles
mv old_name/* new_location/old_name/
```

**Foreign directories — audit before writing.**
Before creating or overwriting any file inside a directory you did not create (e.g., an upstream clone, vendored library, or `external/` subdirectory), run `ls -la` first. Treat existing files as immutable unless explicitly instructed to modify them.

```bash
# ✅ Audit first
ls -la external/some-upstream/
# Only then create a new file, never overwrite existing ones
echo "# index" > external/some-upstream/NOTES.md

# ❌ Blindly overwrite upstream's own README
echo "my notes" > external/some-upstream/README.md
```

## Run Programs With Timeout

When running a program or command that could block (e.g. `cargo run`, dev servers, tests, scripts), use a **reasonable timeout** so the run doesn't hang indefinitely.

| Context | Timeout (guideline) |
|---|---|
| Builds / short commands | ~30–60 s |
| Tests | 60–120 s (or project default) |
| Dev servers / interactive apps | 5–15 s if only confirming startup; use background or no timeout only when the user explicitly wants a long-lived process |

Prefer the runner's timeout (e.g. `timeout` in scripts, or the `timeout` parameter when invoking run/exec).

## MDC Rules Configuration

All `.mdc` files must have YAML frontmatter:
```yaml
---
description: When this rule applies.
alwaysApply: true|false
---
```

Only use `alwaysApply: true` for short, globally applicable rules (< 50 lines). Use `false` for language/domain-specific rules — Cursor loads them contextually.
